list.name: Changes
list.comment: # ================================================ # Subject 50 CHARACTERS HERE ^ # # <type>(<scope>): <subject> # <BLANK LINE> # <body> # <BLANK LINE> # <footer> # # * <type> is usually one of the following: # - fix = bug fix (patch in SemVer) # - feat = new feature (minor in SemVer) # - BREAKING CHANGE = breaking API change (major in SemVer) # # * <type> can also be one of the following: # - build = changes that affect the build system or external # dependencies (adding npm package, yarn package, etc.) # - ci = changes to ci configuration files and scripts # - docs = documentation only changes # - perf = a code change that improves performance # - refactor = a code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a # feature # - style = changes that do not affect the meaning of the code # (white-space, formatting, missing semi-colons, etc.) # - test = adding missing tests or correcting existing tests # # * <scope> will vary from project to project. If you're working on a # project that has a client and a server, it might make sense for a # commit that changes the server code to have have a scope of server. # Optional. # # * <subject> should be capitalized as if it's an email header. It # should be no longer than 50 characters. It should use the # imperative, present tense. # # * <body> should also use the imperative, present tense: "change" not # "changed" nor "changes". The body should include the motivation for # the change and contrast this with previous behavior. Focus on the # "what" and the "why" as opposed to the "how". Hard wrap at 72 # characters. In Vi/Vim/Neovim, use `:set textwidth=72` # (`:set tw=72`) and `:set colorcolumn=72` (`:set cc=72`). Optional. # # * <footer> should include a reference to an issue, if there's a # relevant issue. Optional. # # These rules are based on the following: # * Conventional Commits # https://www.conventionalcommits.org # * Angular Commit Message Guidelines # https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/22b96b9/CONTRIBUTING.md#-commit-message-guidelines # * Tim Pope's Commit Style Guide # https://commit.style # # To use this commit template globally: # `git config --global commit.template /path/to/this/file`
